%I A395621 #35 Jun 17 2026 17:17:11
%S A395621 3,5,10,17,21,26,37,45,70,126,257,283,325,362,368,470,545,612,855,
%T A395621 1118,1275,1827,2232,2670,2845,3348,3690,3794,3828,4670,4917,5544,
%U A395621 6594,6670,6908,7616,9345,9670,10045,11102,13359,16470,17199,17284,19400,22074,24545,25070
%N A395621 Nonsquare integers k > 0 such that there is a nonsquare integer 0 < m < k such that sqrt(k) + sqrt(m) is closer to an integer than for all smaller nonsquare k > m > 0.
%C A395621 It appears that for all k = a(n), the least m < k that yields a new record distance is also the only one to do so. Is that true, or else what is the first exception?
%C A395621 Often, but not always, k = r^2+1 for some r (namely: r = 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 16, 18, 19, ...) and then m = r^2-1, which yields sqrt(k)+sqrt(m) = r(sqrt(1+1/r^2) + sqrt(1-1/r^2)) ~ r(2 - 1/(4 r^4) + O(r^-8)) = 2r - 1/(4 r^3) + O(r^-7).
%C A395621 The successive values of 1/(s - round(s)) with s = sqrt(k) + sqrt(m), rounded to the nearest integer, are 7, -31, -108, -256, -311, -500, -864, -3408, -6660, -15760, -16384, 19716, ..., see A395624.
%C A395621 In the above sequence we note the powers of two 256 and 16384 for a(n) = 17 and 257 (cf. second comment), which might suggest that all k = 4^2^r + 1, r >= 0 are in this sequence. However, for r = 3, 4^2^3+1 = 65537 is no more in the sequence.
%H A395621 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A395621/b395621.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..205</a>
%H A395621 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A395621/a395621.gp.txt">PARI program</a>
%e A395621 The smallest nonsquares k > m > 0 are (3, 2) for which we have sqrt(3) + sqrt(2) = 3.146... which is d = 0.146... away from the nearest integer 3.
%e A395621 The next better solution is k = 5, m = 3 with sqrt(5) + sqrt(3) = 3.968... which is d ~ 0.03 away from the nearest integer 4.
%e A395621 The next better solution is k = 10, m = 8 with sqrt(10) + sqrt(8) = 5.9907... which is d = 0.009 away from the nearest integer 6.
%o A395621 (PARI) d=1; for(b=2, oo, issquare(b)|| for(a=2, b-1, issquare(a) || if(my(t=sqrt(a)+sqrt(b)) || abs(t-=t\/1)<d, d=abs(t); print1(b", "); /*break*/))) \\ This would print k = a(n) twice if there were m < m' < k such that m' yields a better almost-integer than m. This does not seem to happen, so one could uncomment `break` to improve speed, and then better use `forstep(a=b-1,2,-1,...)` instead.
%o A395621 (PARI) \\ See Corneth link
%Y A395621 Cf. A395622 (similar for 3 numbers), A395624 (inverse distance of a(n) from the integers).
